Linear Algebra¶

Linear algebra is a widely used branch of discrete mathematics in machine learning specially in deep learning.

Mathematical objects :-¶

Scalars : Scalars are real numbers combination of which may represent vector or any other linar algebric object. They are written in italic with lowercase.

Vectors : An array of numbers(scalars) arranged in some order. Elements of vector can be thought as co-ordinates in space on different axes. '-' sign is used to index the complement of set.

Matrices : In simple words matrix is 2-D array with the combination of vectors. Usually they are given uppercase with bold tyepface. Each element of matrix can be found by ith and jth element combination. We can identify all the numbers with vertical coordinate i by writing a “:” for the horizontal coordinate.

Tensors : An array of numbers arranged on a regular grid with avariable number of axes is known as a tensor and represented as A.

Operations on objects :-¶

Transpose: Transpose of a Matrix is mirro image of matrix along its diagonal. Transpose of matrix A is represented as A^T.

Broadcasting: Addition of matrix with vectors is possible in linear algebra like C= A + b where b is vector which is added to each row. Such implicit copying of b to many location is broadcasting.

Multiplication: Matrix multiplication is one of the important operation used in linear algebra. A X B = C where A has m X n shape and B has n X p shape then new C matrix will have m X p shape.

Properties of matrix multiplication

Distributive : $A(B + C) = AB + AC$ Associative : $A(BC) = (AB)C$ Not commutative : $AB = BA$ may not be always true.

Identity and Inverse matrix: Identity matrix is a matrix which when divided by with any matrix does not change denoted by I Inverse matrix is nothing but when A matrix is multiplied by its transpose gives answer as identity matrix.

Linear dependence and span: If there are more than one possible solution , to analyze them we can find how many ways are there from origin in order to travel different directions determining how may ways are there to reach b. x specifies the directions. such kind of operations are linear combination. The span of a set of vectors is the set of all points obtainable by linear combinationof the original vectors.

Norms : In machine learning Norms are used to measure the size of the vectors. One norm that commonly arises in machine learning is the $L^∞$ norm,also known as themax norm. This norm simpliﬁes to the absolute value of the element with the largest magnitude in the vector. $||x||∞= maxi|xi$

Eigendecomposition: Matrix decomposition where matrix is divided into eigenvectors and eigenvalues is called as eigedecomposition.

Single value decomposition: Another way to divide matrix is single value decomposition where matrix is divided into singular vectors and singular values.

Principal Component Analysis: The central idea of principal component analysis (PCA) is to decrease the dimensionality of a data set consisting of a big number of interrelated variables, while maintaining as much as reasonable of the variation present in the data set. This is accomplished by changing to a new set of variables, the principal components (PCs), which are uncorrelated, and which are ordered so that the first few retain most of the variation existing in all of the primary variables.

Probability Theory¶

Machine learning should always deal with uncertainties and stochasticity, and hence studying probability theory is important part. There are three possible sources of uncertainty:

1. Inherent stochasticity - This is type of probability where we assume some hypothesis in a random order

2. Incomplete observability - Incomplete observability is the one where outcome of the task is known but we can not observe all variables associated with it.
3. Incomplete modeling - When we discard some variables after observation , those discared variables become uncertainity in predictions which is due to incomplete modeling.

Frequentist probability and Baysian probability are types of probability based on absolute certainity. If we list several properties that we expect common sense reasoning about uncertainty to have, then the only way to satisfy those properties is to treat Bayesian probabilities as behaving exactly the same as frequentist probabilities.

Random variables are variables which can take different values and can be discrete or continuos. Discrete Variables are like points plotted on charts whereas continuos variables can be plotted as a line. Discrete variables are countable and continuos are not countable.

Chain rule of conditional probability :

For 2 variables: P(A,B) = p(A|B) p(B)

For 3 variables: P(A,B,C) = P(A| B,C) P(B,C) = P(A|B,C) P(B|C) P(C)

and in general to n variables: P(A1, A2, ..., An) = P(A1| A2, ..., An) P(A2| A3, ..., An) P(An-1|An) P(An)

Common probability distribution:

1.Bernoulli Distribution- The Bernoulli distribution is a discrete distribution having two possible outcomes labelled by n=0 and n=1 in which n=1 ("success") occurs with probability p and n=0 ("failure") occurs with probability q=1-p, where 0<p<1. It therefore has probability density function. The Bernoulli distribution is the simplest discrete distribution, and it the building block for other more complicated discrete distributions.

2.Multinoulli Distribution- Themultinoulli, orcategorical,distributionis a distribution over a single dis-crete variable withkdiﬀerent states, wherekis ﬁnite.

3.Gaussian Distribution- The Gaussian distribution is a continuous function which approximates the exact binomial distribution of events. The Gaussian distribution shown is normalized so that the sum over all values of x gives a probability of 1.

4.Exponential and Laplace Distributions- In the context of deep learning, we often want to have a probability distribution with a sharp point atx= 0. To accomplish this, we can use the exponential distribution: $p(x; λ) = λ1x≥0exp (−λx)$.

Bay's rule : We often ﬁnd ourselves in a situation where we knowP(y | x) and need to knowP(x | y). Fortunately, if we also knowP(x), we can compute the desired quantityusing Bayes’ rule: $P (x | y) =P (x)P (y | x)/P (y).

Section 1 - Regression¶

1.1 Introduction of data for regression & source¶

This dataset includes a hourly/daily summary for Szeged, Hungary area, between 2006 and 2016.

Data available in the hourly response:

.time
.summary
.precipType
.temperature
.apparentTemperature
.humidity
.windSpeed
.windBearing
.visibility
.loudCover
.pressure

Source of the data¶

https://www.kaggle.com/budincsevity/szeged-weather

df1= df1[(df1['Formatted Date'] < '2006-01-02')]

In [141]:
t = df1['Formatted Date']
data1 = df1['Temperature (C)']
data2 = df1['Humidity']

fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(figsize=(16,8))

color = 'tab:red'
ax1.set_xlabel('time (Hour)')
ax1.set_ylabel('Temprature', color=color)
ax1.plot(t, data1, color=color)

ax1.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)

ax2 = ax1.twinx()  # instantiate a second axes that shares the same x-axis

color = 'tab:blue'
ax2.set_ylabel('Humidity', color=color)  # we already handled the x-label with ax1
ax2.plot(t, data2, color=color)
ax2.tick_params(axis='y', labelcolor=color)
fig.tight_layout()  # otherwise the right y-label is slightly clipped
plt.show()

Observations:

  • As temperature increases , humidity is decreasing in a day per hour.

6. Yearwise visibility ratio in rain and snowy weather¶

In [143]:
df_yearwise = df_reg.copy()
df_yearwise['Formatted Date'] = pd.DatetimeIndex(df_yearwise['Formatted Date']).year
df_grp= df_yearwise.groupby(['Formatted Date','Precip Type']).mean().reset_index()


rain_visibility = list(df_grp[(df_grp['Precip Type'] == 'rain')]['Visibility (km)'])
snow_visibility = list(df_grp[(df_grp['Precip Type'] == 'snow')]['Visibility (km)'])
years = df_grp['Formatted Date'].unique()
barWidth = 0.25
rain = np.arange(len(rain_visibility))
snow= [x + barWidth for x in rain]
plt.figure(figsize = (16, 8))
plt.bar(rain, rain_visibility, color='blue', width=barWidth, edgecolor='black', label='rain')
plt.bar(snow, snow_visibility, color='orange', width=barWidth, edgecolor='black', label='snow')
###
plt.xlabel('Year', fontweight='bold')
plt.xticks([r + barWidth for r in range(len(rain_visibility))], years)
plt.ylabel('Average visibility', fontweight='bold')
###
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Observations:

  • It can be seen clearly in rainy weather visibility is good as compared to snowy weather.
  • In 2010 average visibility was lesser than other years.
  • In 2016 average visibility was best.

7.In 2012 temperature fell below 0 degree celsius in jan and also it was highest in same year in july month.

Section 2 - Classification¶

2.1 Introduction of data classification & source¶

Black Friday shopping data from retail store¶

This dataset consists of 550 000 observations of the transactions made in a retail store. It contains different types of variables like User id, Product Id, customer age group, city category, stay in current city year, martital status of the customer etc. This data set aims to predict patterns between different features.

Source of the data¶

https://www.kaggle.com/mehdidag/black-friday
